Here's the fix:
Step 1 — Install Guest Additions inside the VM
In the VirtualBox menu bar at the top of the VM window:
Devices → Insert Guest Additions CD Image...
This mounts a virtual CD inside the VM. Open File Explorer inside the VM → you'll see a CD drive (usually D: or E:) labeled VirtualBox Guest Additions.
Double-click it → run VBoxWindowsAdditions.exe → click through the installer → reboot the VM when prompted.
Step 2 — Verify the shared folder appears
After reboot, open File Explorer inside the VM. The shared folder should appear under:

Network → VBOXSVR → ClaudeProjects, or
As a mapped drive letter (Z: or similar) if you checked Auto-mount

If it still doesn't show after Guest Additions
Open Command Prompt as Administrator inside the VM and run:
cmdnet use Z: \\vboxsvr\ClaudeProjects /persistent:yes
That manually maps it to Z: permanently.
Why this happens
VirtualBox shared folders use a kernel-level driver that only exists after Guest Additions is installed. Without it, the folder setting exists in VirtualBox's config but the VM has no driver to actually mount it — so it silently does nothing.
